**Abstract:**
Extensive quotations from Richard Rorty's "Philosophy and the Mirror of Nature" (1979) on the history of epistemology. Includes passages on analytic philosophy as Kantian variant, Wittgenstein's tool-conception of language, the Greek contrast between contemplation and action, hylemorphic vs. representative models of knowledge, and the difference between Aristotelian intentional identity and Cartesian mental representations.

**AI Recommendation:** Reading notes on Rorty; relates to critique of mirror-of-nature epistemology.

